Definition 1.3. The category of (classical) simplices $\Delta$ is defined to be the full subcategory of the category of categories generated by the categories (induced by the linear orders on) $\Delta^{n}:=\{0,1,\ldots,n\}$, with $n\in{\mathbb{N}}$.
Definition 9.3. An equivalence relation $\equiv$ on $\mathrm{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}$ is called admissible if it implies $||$ and is compatible with composition of morphisms.
Definition 4.5. Let $A\in{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}$. The boundary $\partial A\subset A$ is defined to be the union of all faces of $A$. It is the largest proper $\trianglerighteqslant$ -simplicial subset of $A$.
Definition 12.1. Define the functor $\mathfrak{L}\colon{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$% \trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}\rightarrow{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny\Delta}}$ to be the Yoneda extension of the functor ${\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}% \rightarrow{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny\Delta}},\,A=(A_{1},A_{2},\ldots)\mapsto(A_{1}% \times A_{2}\times\ldots)/{\sim}$, where for $x,y\in(A_{1}\times A_{2}\times\ldots)(B)$, with $B\in\Delta$, we declare that $x\sim y$ if there is $k\in{\mathbb{N}}_{+}$ such that for all $n\in{\mathbb{N}}_{+}$ with $n\leq k$ we have $x_{n}=y_{n}$ and $x_{k}=y_{k}$ is constant. Denote by $\mathfrak{R}\colon{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny\Delta}}\rightarrow{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{% \raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}$ a right adjoint to $\mathfrak{L}$.
Definition 6.3. A morphism $f\colon X\rightarrow Y$ is called inner anodyne if it has the left lifting property with respect to every inner fibration.
Definition 2.2. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a very rigid category. Denote the class of sections in $\mathcal{A}$ by $\mathcal{A}_{+}$, and the class of retractions in $\mathcal{A}$ by $\mathcal{A}_{-}$. Then $\mathcal{A}$ is called a category of cells if (i) The pair $(\mathcal{A}_{-},\mathcal{A}_{+})$ is a (strict) factorization system. (ii) Every retraction is determined by its sections. (iii) Every section is determined by its retractions. (iv) The order on $\mathrm{Ob}(\mathcal{A})$ defined by $\mathcal{A}_{+}$, which is equal to the order defined by $(\mathcal{A}_{-})^{\mathrm{op}}$, is well-founded.
Definition 6.11. Denote by $\tau\colon{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$% \trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}\rightarrow\mathrm{Cat}^{\mathrm{% strict}}$ a left adjoint to the inclusion $\mathrm{Cat}^{\mathrm{strict}}\subset{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{% \begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}$. The functor $\tau$ can be constructed completely analogous to the way Joyal contructs his functor $\tau_{1}\colon{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny\Delta}}\rightarrow\mathrm{Cat}^{\mathrm{% strict}}_{\Delta}$, where $\mathrm{Cat}^{\mathrm{strict}}_{\Delta}\subset{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny\Delta}}$ shall denote the full subcategory of (classical) categories.
Definition 3.1. Define $\mathcal{A}:=\prod^{\prime}_{n\in{\mathbb{N}}_{+}}\Delta\subset\prod_{n\in{% \mathbb{N}}_{+}}\Delta$ to be the full subcategory generated by the objects which have only finitely many components not equal to $\Delta^{0}$. For morphisms $f,g\colon A\rightarrow B$ in $\mathcal{A}$, define $f\sim g$ if and only if there is $k\in\mathbb{N}_{+}$ such that $f_{1}=g_{1},\ldots,f_{k}=g_{k}$ and $f_{k}=g_{k}$ is constant, i. e. factors through $\Delta^{0}$. This defines an equivalence relation on the set of morphisms in $\mathcal{A}$ which is compatible with composition of morphisms. Define ${\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}% \subset\mathcal{A}/{\sim}$ to be the full subcategory generated by the objects $A=(A_{1},A_{2},\ldots)$ having the property that there is $k\in\mathbb{N}$ such that for all $n\in\mathbb{N}_{+}$, we have $A_{n}=\Delta^{0}$ if and only if $n>k$. For $A\in\mathcal{A}$, define $\mathrm{dim}(A)$ to be the smallest $k\in{\mathbb{N}}$ such that $A_{k+1}=\Delta^{0}$. For a morphism $f\colon A\rightarrow B$ in $\mathcal{A}$, define $\mathrm{deg}(f)$ to be the smallest $k\in{\mathbb{N}}_{+}$ such that $f_{k}$ is constant. (We have $\mathrm{deg}(f)\leq\mathrm{dim}(A)+1$ and $\mathrm{deg}(f)\leq\mathrm{dim}(B)+1$.)
Definition 1.7. If $u\colon A\rightarrow B$ and $v\colon S\rightarrow T$ are two morphisms in $\mathcal{T}$, we denote by $u\times^{\prime}v$ the canonical morphism $A\times T\sqcup_{A\times S}B\times S\rightarrow B\times T$.
Definition 5.2. A cat is called grumpy if …
Definition 10.1. For $A\in{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}$, define the spine $I(A)\subset A$ to be $\trianglerighteqslant$ -simplicial subset that contains a simplex $s\colon B\rightarrow A$ (with $B\in{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}$) if and only if $s_{k}\colon B_{k}\rightarrow A_{k}$ is contained in $I(A_{k})\subset A_{k}\in\Delta$ for $k\in\{1,\ldots,n\}$, where $n:=\mathrm{deg}(s)$.
Definition 5.5. Define $\mathrm{Grpd}\subset{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$% \trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}$ to be the full subcategory generated by the groupoids, and define $\mathrm{Grpd}^{\mathrm{strict}}\subset\mathrm{Grpd}$ to be the full subcategory generated by the strict groupoids.
Definition 4.2. Let $f\colon B\hookrightarrow A$ be an abstract face, and define $k:=\mathrm{dim}(A)$. Then $k+1\geq\mathrm{deg}(f)\geq k$, and the components $f_{1},\ldots,f_{k}$ of $f$ are (well-defined) monomorphisms in $\Delta$. The face $f$ is called inner if there is $m\in\{1,\ldots,k\}$ such that $f_{m}$ is an inner face (in $\Delta$). If $f$ is inner, then for $n\in\{1,\ldots,k\}-\{m\}$ the monomorphism $f_{n}$ is the identity on $A_{n}$.
Definition 9.1. For $n\in{\mathbb{N}}$, define the abstract $n$-morphism $I^{n}\in{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$% \end{sideways}}}$ by $I^{n}:={\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$% \end{sideways}}}^{1,\ldots,1}$, with $n$ many 1s. The elements of $\mathcal{C}(I^{n})$ are called $n$-morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$. Define $\mathrm{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}:=\sqcup_{n\in{\mathbb{N}}}\mathcal{C}(I^{n})$ to be the set of all morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 1.1. Define ${\mathbb{N}}:=\{0,1,2,\ldots\}$ and ${\mathbb{N}}_{+}:={\mathbb{N}}-\{0\}$.
Definition 7.1. Define the $\trianglerighteqslant$ -simplicial set ${\color[rgb]{1,0,0}{\mathbf{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$% \trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}}$ by ${\color[rgb]{1,0,0}{\mathbf{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$% \trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}}(A):=\{(x_{0},\ldots,x_{m};\,\alpha_{% 1},\ldots,\alpha_{m})\ |\ x_{i}\in\mathrm{Ob}({\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-% 1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}),\,\alpha_{i}% \in{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$% \trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}(x_{i-1},x_{i})(A^{\prime})\}$ for $A\in{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}$, where $A_{1}=\Delta^{m}$, $A^{\prime}:=(A_{2},A_{3},\ldots)$ and where ${\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$% \end{sideways}}}}}(x_{i-1},x_{i})$ denotes the $\trianglerighteqslant$ -simplicial set of morphisms from $x_{i-1}$ to $x_{i}$.
Definition 3.2. For $k\in\mathbb{N}$ and $a_{1},\ldots,a_{k}\in\mathbb{N}_{+}$, define ${\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}^{a_% {1},\ldots,a_{k}}:=(\Delta^{a_{1}},\ldots,\Delta^{a_{k}},\Delta^{0},\Delta^{0}% ,\ldots)\in{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$% \end{sideways}}}.$ In particular, ${\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}^{% \emptyset}=(\Delta^{0},\Delta^{0},\ldots)$.
Definition 9.6. Let $\equiv$ be an admissible equivalence relation on $\mathrm{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}$. For $x,y\in\mathrm{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}$ with $x\,||\,y$, define $x\equiv^{+}y$ if and only if there are morphisms $u\colon x\rightarrow y$, $v\colon y\rightarrow x$ such that $vu\equiv 1_{x}$ and $uv\equiv 1_{y}$. This defines an admissible equivalence relation $\equiv^{+}$ on $\mathrm{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 1.4. For a (small) category $\mathcal{A}$, define ${\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny\mathcal{A}}}$ to be the category of functors $\mathcal{A}^{\mathrm{op}}\rightarrow\mathrm{Set}$, with natural transformations as morphisms.
Definition 10.4. A morphism $f\colon X\rightarrow Y$ in ${\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$% \end{sideways}}}}}$ is called a cat fibration if it has the right lifting property with respect to every cat anodyne morphism. Denote the class of cat fibrations by $\mathcal{F}$.
Definition 4.4. Let $A\in{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}$. Fix a face $B\subset A$, and let $\Lambda\subset A$ be the union of all faces of $A$ except $B$. $\Lambda\subset A$ is called the horn of $A$ corresponding to the face $B$. It is called an inner horn if the missing face is inner.
Definition 9.2. Two $n$-morphisms $x,y$ in $\mathcal{C}$ ($n\in\mathbb{N}_{0}$) are called parallel, written $x\,||\,y$, if either $n>0$ and both source and both target $(n-1)$-morphisms of $x$ and $y$ are equal, or if $n=0$, as there is neither a source nor a target morphism in this case.
Definition 2.1. A category $\mathcal{S}$ is called skeletal if no two distinct objects in $\mathcal{S}$ are isomorphic. An object $A$ in a category $\mathcal{A}$ is called rigid if the identity on $A$ is the only automorphism of $A$. A category is called rigid if every object is rigid. A category is called very rigid if it is rigid and skeletal. A very rigid category is called a quasi-order if it contains no endomorphisms except the identities. For two objects $A,B$ in a quasi-order, we define $A\preceq B$ to hold if and only if there is a morphism from $A$ to $B$. A quasi-order $\mathcal{A}$ is called well-founded if the induced order $\preceq$ on $\mathrm{Ob}(\mathcal{A})$ is well-founded.
Definition 6.1. A morphism $f\colon X\rightarrow Y$ in ${\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$% \end{sideways}}}}}$ is called an inner fibration if it has the right lifting property with respect to every inner horn.
Definition 1.10. If $u\colon A\rightarrow B$ and $v\colon X\rightarrow Y$ are two morphisms in $\mathcal{T}$, we denote by $\langle u,f\rangle$ the canonical morphism $X^{B}\rightarrow Y^{B}\times_{Y^{A}}X^{A}$.
Definition 5.4. $\mathcal{G}\in{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$% \trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}$ is called a groupoid if for every horn $\Lambda\subset A$ the map $\mathcal{G}(A)\rightarrow\mathcal{G}(\Lambda)$ is surjective. A groupoid $\mathcal{G}$ is called strict if for every horn $\Lambda\subset A$ the map $\mathcal{G}(A)\rightarrow\mathcal{G}(\Lambda)$ is bijective.
Definition 9.10. A morphism $f\colon X\rightarrow Y$ in ${\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$% \end{sideways}}}}}$ is called a weak cat equivalence if for every $\mathcal{C}\in\mathrm{Cat}$, the morphism $\mathcal{C}^{f}\colon\mathcal{C}^{Y}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}^{X}$ is an equivalence in ${\color[rgb]{1,0,0}\mathbf{Cat}}$. Denote the class of weak cat equivalences by $\mathcal{W}$. The weak equivalences are also called acyclic morphisms. An acyclic monomorphism is also called a cat anodyne morphism.
Definition 4.1. Let $A\in{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}$. The maximal proper subobjects $B\hookrightarrow A$ (in $\trianglerighteqslant$ ) are called abstract faces of $A$. The image of the corresponding monomorphism $B\hookrightarrow A$ (in ${\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$% \end{sideways}}}}}$) is called a face of $A\in{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$% \trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}$.
Definition 8.1. Define the (strict) cat $\hat{\mathcal{C}}:=\mathrm{Fun}(\mathcal{C}^{\mathrm{op}},{\color[rgb]{1,0,0}% \mathbf{Cat^{strict}}})$ and the Yoneda functor $\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\hat{\mathcal{C}},\,x\mapsto\mathcal{C}(-,x)$.
Definition 2.3. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a well-founded quasi-order. Define $\Sigma_{-1}:=\emptyset$, and for $n\in{\mathbb{N}}$, define $\Sigma_{n}\subset\mathrm{Ob}(\mathcal{A})$ to be the set of objects $A$ having the property that $B\in\Sigma_{n-1}$ for all objects $B$ with $B\prec A$. We have $\emptyset=\Sigma_{-1}\subset\Sigma_{0}\subset\Sigma_{1}\subset\ldots$ and $\cup_{n}\Sigma_{n}=\mathrm{Ob}(\mathcal{A})$. For $A\in\mathcal{A}$, denote by $\mathrm{deg}(A)$ the smallest $n\in{\mathbb{N}}$ such that $A\in\Sigma_{n}$. This defines a function $\mathrm{deg}\colon\mathrm{Ob}(\mathcal{A})\rightarrow{\mathbb{N}}$.
Definition 5.1. $\mathcal{C}\in{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$% \trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}$ is called a cat if for every inner horn $\Lambda\subset A$ the map $\mathcal{C}(A)\rightarrow\mathcal{C}(\Lambda)$ is surjective. A cat $\mathcal{C}$ is called strict if for every inner horn $\Lambda\subset A$ the map $\mathcal{C}(A)\rightarrow\mathcal{C}(\Lambda)$ is bijective.
Definition 9.4. Let $\simeq$ be the coarsest reflexive relation on $\mathrm{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}$ having the property that for all $x\,||\,y$ in $\mathrm{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}$, we have $x\simeq y$ if there are morphisms $u\colon x\rightarrow y$, $v\colon y\rightarrow x$ such that $vu\simeq 1_{x}$ and $uv\simeq 1_{y}$. We write $u\colon x\xrightarrow{\,\smash{\raisebox{-1.72pt}{$\scriptstyle\sim$}}\,}y$ (and $v\colon y\xrightarrow{\,\smash{\raisebox{-1.72pt}{$\scriptstyle\sim$}}\,}x$), and call the morphisms $u$ and $v$ equivalences.
Definition 1.5. A morphism in $\mathcal{T}$ is called a trivial fibration if it has the right lifting property with respect to every monomorphism.
Definition 4.1. Let $U\subseteq\coprod_{i=1}^{n}X$. An assignment $s\in\mathcal{E}(U)$ is said to be codiagonal if it satisfies $\forall_{x\in X}\boldsymbol{.}\;\,\forall_{i,j\in\{1,\ldots,n\}}\boldsymbol{.}% \;\,\langle x,i\rangle,\langle x,j\rangle\in U\implies s(\langle x,i\rangle)=s% (\langle x,j\rangle);$ i.e. copies of the same measurement at different sites are assigned the same outcome. Equivalently, in categorical terms, an assignment $s:U\rightarrow O$ is codiagonal when it factors as $\xymatrix{U\ar@{{}^{(}->}[r]&\coprod_{i=1}^{n}\ar[r]^{~{}\;\;\bigtriangledown_% {{}_{n}}}X&X\ar[r]&O}.$ We denote the set of such assignments by $\mathcal{E}^{\triangledown}(U)$.
Definition 3.2. Let $\mathcal{M}\preceq\mathcal{M}^{\prime}$, and let $e$ be a model defined on $\mathcal{M}$. A model $f$ on $\mathcal{M}^{\prime}$ is said to extend $e$ if $\forall_{D\in\mathcal{M}}\boldsymbol{.}\;\qquad f_{D}=e_{D}.$ When such an $f$ exists, we say that $e$ is extendable to $\mathcal{M}^{\prime}$.
Definition 2.6. If an empirical model is not possibilistically extendable to a global section we say that the model is logically contextual (or logically non-local when appropriate).
Definition 2.2. An empirical model $e$ over a measurement scenario $(X,O,\mathcal{M})$ is a compatible family of $R$-distributions $\{e_{C}\}_{C\in\mathcal{M}},$ with $e_{C}\in\mathcal{D}_{R}\mathcal{E}(C)$ for each $C\in\mathcal{M}$.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathcal{M}\preceq\mathcal{M}^{\prime}$ and $e$ be a model on $\mathcal{M}$. For each $C\in\mathcal{M}^{\prime}$ and $s\in\mathcal{E}(C)$, we define: $e^{\prime}_{C}(s):=\bigwedge_{W\subseteq C,W\in\downarrow\!\mathcal{M}}e_{W}(s% |_{W}).$ If $\{e^{\prime}_{C}\}_{C\in\mathcal{M}^{\prime}}$ is a well-defined model extending $e$, we call it the canonical extension of $e$ to $\mathcal{M}^{\prime}$, and say that $e$ is canonically extendable to $\mathcal{M}^{\prime}$.
Definition 2.8. Let $O=\{0,1\}$, and $\mathcal{M}$ be a cover of $X$ for which there exists $n\in\mathbb{N}$ such that $\forall_{C\in\mathcal{M}}\boldsymbol{.}\;\left|C\right|=n$. The Kochen-Specker model on the measurement scenario $(X,O,\mathcal{M})$ is the possibilistic model $\{e_{C}\}_{C\in\mathcal{M}}$ defined by $S_{e}(C)=S_{\mathsf{KS}}(C):=\left\{s\in\mathcal{E}(C)\mid o(s)=1\right\},$ for all $C\in\mathcal{M}$, where $o(s):=|\left\{x\in C\mid s(x)=1\right\}|$ for any assignment $s\in\mathcal{E}(C)$.
Definition 3.8. Let $e$ be a model on $\mathcal{M}$. For any $U\subseteq X$, the induced sub-model of $e$ on $U$ is $\{e_{U\cap C}\}_{C\in\mathcal{M}}$.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{M}$ and $\mathcal{M}^{\prime}$ be two measurement covers. We write $\mathcal{M}\preceq\mathcal{M}^{\prime}$ when $\downarrow\!\mathcal{M}\subseteq\downarrow\!\mathcal{M}^{\prime}$; i.e. $\forall_{D\in\mathcal{M}}\boldsymbol{.}\;\quad\exists_{C\in\mathcal{M}^{\prime% }}\boldsymbol{.}\;\quad D\subseteq C.$
Definition 2.7. If no global assignment is consistent with the support of the model $e$, i.e. $S_{e}(X)=\emptyset$, we say that $e$ is strongly contextual (or strongly non-local, when appropriate).
Definition 2.1. We will refer to $(X,O,\mathcal{M})$ as a measurement scenario.
Definition 4.2. With any empirical model $f$ defined on a measurement scenario $(X,O,\mathcal{P}_{n}X)$ we associate an $n$-partite empirical model $f^{\mathsf{Bell}}$ on the Bell scenario $(\coprod_{i=1}^{n}X,O,\prod_{i=1}^{n}X)$ defined by $f^{\mathsf{Bell}}_{C}(s)=\begin{cases}f_{\underline{C}}(\underline{s})&\text{% if $s\in\mathcal{E}^{\triangledown}(C)$}\\ 0&\text{if $s\not\in\mathcal{E}^{\triangledown}(C)$}\end{cases}.$
Definition 3.3. For any cover $\mathcal{M}$ we define $n(\mathcal{M}):=\max_{C\in\mathcal{M}}\left|C\right|$ to be the maximum size of contexts in $\mathcal{M}$ (where no confusion arises as to the cover in question this will be simply denoted $n$). Then we can define another cover $\mathcal{P}_{n}X:=\left\{Y\subseteq X\mid|Y|=n\right\}$ over $X$. It necessarily holds that $\mathcal{M}\preceq\mathcal{P}_{n}X$.
Definition 4.4 An ${\cal M}$-graded monoidal category ${\cal C}$ with data services in ${\cal C}^{\natural}_{0}$ is an ${\cal M}$-graded monoidal computer if it carries the following structure for all $A,B\in{\cal C}$: (I) a family ${\cal C}^{\natural}_{0}(X,{\mathbb{P}})\xrightarrow{\gamma^{AB}_{X}}{\cal C}(% XA,B)$ of surjections natural in $X$, (II) families $\sigma_{X}^{A}$, $\tau_{X}^{A}$ and $\vartheta_{X}^{A}$, all natural in $X$, such that the following diagrams commute
Definition 3.4 A predicate in a monoidal computer ${\cal C}$ is a computation $\alpha\in{\cal C}(A,\mathbb{2})$, where the type $\mathbb{2}$ of booleans is a type where ${\cal C}^{\natural}(\mathbb{2})\cong\{0,1\}$.
Definition 4.2 We say that a computation $I\xrightarrow{a}A$ halts if there is $m<\infty$ such that $a=a\!\!\restriction_{m}$. More generally, we say that $A\xrightarrow{f}B$ halts if the composite $I\xrightarrow{a}A\xrightarrow{f}B$ halts whenever $a$ halts. The subcategory of total functions that halt is denoted ${\cal C}_{\natural}$, and thus $\displaystyle{\cal C}_{\natural}(A,B)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\bigcup_{m<\infty}{\cal C}_{m}^{\natural}(A,B)$
Definition 2.1 A data service over an object $A$ of a monoidal category ${\cal C}$ consists of • the copying operation $A\xrightarrow{\delta}A\otimes A$, • the deleting operation $A\xrightarrow{{\scriptstyle\top}}I$, and • the comparison operation $A\otimes A\xrightarrow{\varrho}A$ such that • $\delta$ and $\varrho$ are associative, • ${\scriptstyle\top}$ is the unit of $\delta$, • $\delta$ and $\varrho$ satisfy the data distribution conditions.
Definition 4.1 A category ${\cal C}$ is ${\cal M}$-graded if every hom-set ${\cal C}(A,B)$ comes with (i) grading ${\cal C}(A,B)\xrightarrow{\left\|{-}\right\|}{\cal M}$, which induces the graded hom-sets $\displaystyle{\cal C}_{n}(A,B)\ =\ \{f\in{\cal C}(A,B)\ |\ \left\|{f}\right\|% \leq n\}$ the elements of which we write as $f_{n}$; (ii) restriction $\restriction_{n}\ :\ {\cal C}(A,B)\rightarrow{\cal C}_{n}(A,B)$ for every $n\in\overline{\mathbb{N}}$ where for all $f_{m}\in{\cal C}_{m}(A,B)$ holds $\displaystyle(f_{m})\!\!\restriction_{n}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle f_{m\wedge n}$ We require that identity morphisms are of grade 0, and $\displaystyle\left\|{{f}\hskip 0.86pt;{g}}\right\|$ $\displaystyle\leq$ $\displaystyle\left\|{f}\right\|\oplus\left\|{g}\right\|$ which makes the following diagram commute $\tikzcd[ampersandreplacement=\&]{\cal C}_{\ell}(A,B)\times{\cal C}_{n}(B,C)% \arrow[rightarrow]{r}{(\,;)}\arrow[rightarrow]{d}[swap]{{\rm id}\times% \restriction_{m}}\&{\cal C}_{\ell\oplus n}(A,C)\arrow[rightarrow]{d}{% \restriction_{\ell\oplus m}}\\ {\cal C}_{\ell}(A,B)\times{\cal C}_{m}(B,C)\arrow[rightarrow]{r}{(\,;)}\&{\cal C% }_{\ell\oplus m}(A,C)$ An ${\cal M}$-graded monoidal category is a monoidal category ${\cal C}$, which is ${\cal M}$-graded in the above sense, with all monoidal isomorphisms (such as $A\otimes B\xrightarrow{\varsigma}B\otimes A$) of grade 0, and moreover $\displaystyle\left\|{f\otimes t}\right\|$ $\displaystyle\leq$ $\displaystyle\left\|{f}\right\|\oplus\left\|{t}\right\|$ making the following diagram commute $\tikzcd[ampersandreplacement=\&,columnsep=small]{\cal C}_{\ell}(A,B)\times{% \cal C}_{n}(P,Q)\arrow[rightarrow]{r}{\otimes}\arrow[rightarrow]{d}[swap]{% \restriction_{k}\times\restriction_{m}}\&{\cal C}_{\ell\oplus n}(AP,BQ)\arrow[% rightarrow]{d}{\restriction_{k\oplus m}}\\ {\cal C}_{k}(A,B)\times{\cal C}_{m}(P,Q)\arrow[rightarrow]{r}{\otimes}\&{\cal C% }_{k\oplus m}(AP,BQ)$
